# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: adelaide-footy-league
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:adelaide-footy-league/1911-saafl-season] The **1911 SAAFL season** was the inaugural season of the **South Australian Amateur Football League** (SAAFL).
[src:adelaide-footy-league/1911-saafl-season] The 1911 season commenced on 6th May and concluded on 16 September.
[src:adelaide-footy-league/1911-saafl-season] University won the inaugural premiership, after finishing first on the ladder and finishing the season undefeated.
[src:adelaide-footy-league/1911-saafl-season] Five clubs competed in the inaugural SAAFL season - Glenferrie, Marlborough, St.
[src:adelaide-footy-league/1911-saafl-season] Matches were played at University Oval, Price Oval, and Jubilee Oval.
[src:adelaide-footy-league/1911-saafl-season] On the 29th July, a combined team played the Gawler Association and won 14.12 (96) to 4.4 (28).
[src:adelaide-footy-league/1911-saafl-season] Goalkickers: Middleton 3, Wilton 3, Giles 2, Grantley 2, Blacket 1, Jervois 1.
[src:adelaide-footy-league/1912-saafl-season] The **1912 SAAFL season** was the 2nd season of the **South Australian Amateur Football League (SAAFL)**.
[src:adelaide-footy-league/1912-saafl-season] The 1912 season commenced on 6th May and concluded on 7th September.
[src:adelaide-footy-league/1912-saafl-season] The league increased the number of teams from 5 to 7 with the acceptance of Semaphore Central and St.
[src:adelaide-footy-league/1912-saafl-season] An application was denied from Prospect for the second year in a row.
[src:adelaide-footy-league/1912-saafl-season] Matches were played at University Oval, Prince Alfred College, St.
[src:adelaide-footy-league/1912-saafl-season] Peters College, Jubilee Oval and in the south parklands opposite the Parkside Hotel.
[src:adelaide-footy-league/1913-saafl-season] The season commenced on 3rd May and concluded 27th September.
[src:adelaide-footy-league/1913-saafl-season] The League Received applications from Albert Park, Alberton Baptist, Kenilworth, Kingswood, Prince Alfred College and Stanley Street.
[src:adelaide-footy-league/1913-saafl-season] Kingswood and Prince Alfred College were accepted as the SAAFL decided to take no more than two new clubs, this increased the League from 7 to 9 teams.
[src:adelaide-footy-league/1913-saafl-season] New Ovals to be added for this season are Price Oval, Kingswood's ground on Park Terrace (now Greenhill Road) opposite Methodist Ladies College (now Annesley Junior School) and an oval on the corner of South Terrace and Pulteney Street.
[src:adelaide-footy-league/1913-saafl-season] On Monday, 23rd June a combined team defeated the Gawler Association 10.13 (73) to 5.7 (37).
[src:adelaide-footy-league/1913-saafl-season] SAAFL Goalkickers: Fraser (St.Barts) 5, Rayner (PAC) 4 and Matters (Kingswood) 1.
[src:adelaide-footy-league/1913-saafl-season] Best Players: Rayner, Mengersen (PAC), J.W.
[src:adelaide-footy-league/1913-saafl-season] Limb (Uni), Dreyer (PAC), Daw (Kingswood), Matters and Fraser.
[src:adelaide-footy-league/1914-saafl-season] The **1914 SAAFL season** was the 4th season of the **South Australian Amateur Football League (SAAFL)**.
[src:adelaide-footy-league/1914-saafl-season] The 1914 season commenced on 2nd May and concluded 19th September.
[src:adelaide-footy-league/1914-saafl-season] Inaugural member Marlborough could not form a team, so it was decided to replace them with Kenilworth, a club from the United Church Association and premiers in 1913.
[src:adelaide-footy-league/1915-saafl-season] The 1915 season commenced on 1st May and concluded on 28th August.
[src:adelaide-footy-league/1915-saafl-season] Bartholomew went into recess and didn't reappear until 1924 in the United Church Association.
[src:adelaide-footy-league/1915-saafl-season] It was suggested for the first time that players wear numbers on the guernseys so the spectators could identify the players, this recommendation was not taken up until 1924.
[src:adelaide-footy-league/1915-saafl-season] With the increasing concern over the state of the War, it was decided that the finals when only two teams (University and Prince Alfred College) had completed their minor round matches.
[src:adelaide-footy-league/1915-saafl-season] This season has the first reference to the **Naylor Medal** (named after Professor Darnley Naylor, the SAAFL President) for the best player in the SAAFL.
[src:adelaide-footy-league/1915-saafl-season] It was decided on a 7-2 vote that as Kingswood had a much better percentage than University, it would be awarded the minor premiership.
[src:adelaide-footy-league/1920-saafl-season] The 1920 season commenced on 1st May and concluded on 11th September.
[src:adelaide-footy-league/1920-saafl-season] *et al.* The League received applications from Prospect, East Adelaide (formerly in the Adelaide Association) and Grange (formerly in the United Suburban Association), the latter two being admitted.
[src:adelaide-footy-league/1920-saafl-season] Prospect played the 1920 season in the YMCA Assocation.
[src:adelaide-footy-league/1920-saafl-season] East Adelaide's ground is not know, but Grange played at Grange Oval, and before the season merged with Henley Beach to form Henley and Grange.
[src:adelaide-footy-league/1920-saafl-season] A match between University and Prince Alfred College on University Oval had to be abandoned just after half time when a heavy downpour flooded the oval.
[src:adelaide-footy-league/1920-saafl-season] The match was awarded to University as it was leading at the time.
[src:adelaide-footy-league/1920-saafl-season] In another match, between Semaphore Central and Kingswood, at three-quarter time the score was Semaphore 3.5 to Kingswood 3.4.
[src:adelaide-footy-league/1920-saafl-season] However it was discovered Kingswood had nineteen men on the field, and so its score to that point was cancelled.
[src:adelaide-footy-league/1920-saafl-season] Semaphore thus began the last quarter leading 3.5 to nil.
[src:adelaide-footy-league/1920-saafl-season] However, Kingswood were able to kick five straight goals in the last quarter and won the match by one point.
[src:adelaide-footy-league/1921-saafl-season] The **1921 SAAFL season** was the 7th season of the **South Australian Amateur Football League** (SAAFL).
[src:adelaide-footy-league/1921-saafl-season] Prospect, who had previously applied in 1911, 1912 and 1920, was at last accepted.
[src:adelaide-footy-league/1921-saafl-season] Prospect replaced East Adelaide who moved to the YMCA Football Association.
[src:adelaide-footy-league/adelaide-footy-league-p01] The **Adelaide Footy League** (**AdFL**), formerly known as the **South Australian Amateur Football League** (**SAAFL**), is a semi-professional Australian rules football competition based in Adelaide, South Australia.
[src:adelaide-footy-league/adelaide-footy-league-p01] Comprising sixty-seven member clubs playing over one hundred and ten matches per week, the league is one of Australia's largest Australian rules football associations.
[src:adelaide-footy-league/adelaide-footy-league-p01] The league currently provides competition across eight Senior divisions with Reserves grades, accompanied by a separate C grade competition, all from Divisions 1 to 7.
[src:adelaide-footy-league/adelaide-footy-league-p01] The league was officially formed on 8 March 1911 and the first match was played on 6 May 1911.
[src:adelaide-footy-league/adelaide-footy-league-p01] With the exception of recesses during the two World Wars, the competition has been continuous since that time.
[src:adelaide-footy-league/adelaide-footy-league-p01] Adelaide University Football Club was keen to field a team in the SAFA competition and applied each year from 1906 to 1910.
[src:adelaide-footy-league/adelaide-footy-league-p01] Each time the application was rejected as it was felt the inclusion of a university team would threaten the electorate system.
[src:adelaide-footy-league/adelaide-footy-league-p01] In 1910 the Adelaide University Sports Association thought the case for admission to SAFA would be strengthened if the University had a team playing successfully in regular competition.
[src:adelaide-footy-league/adelaide-footy-league-p01] It was felt that this could be achieved by forming a purely amateur league with other clubs not already in an association.
[src:adelaide-footy-league/adelaide-footy-league-p01] By late 1910 Glenferrie, Marlborough and St.
[src:adelaide-footy-league/adelaide-footy-league-p01] Bartholomew clubs had agreed to join with University to form the new association based on amateur principles.
[src:adelaide-footy-league/adelaide-footy-league-p01] By 1911, as preparations were in hand for the inaugural season, the four clubs had become five with the inclusion of St.
[src:adelaide-footy-league/adelaide-footy-league-p01] The clubs also had agreed to admit late applicant Semaphore Central for the 1912 season.
[src:adelaide-footy-league/adelaide-footy-league-p01] In that first season only three ovals were used for matches – Jubilee Oval (Adelaide), Price Oval and University Oval.
[src:adelaide-footy-league/adelaide-footy-league-p01] Price Oval (now known as Hawthorn Oval) in Mitcham and University Oval (at the corner of Sir Edwin Smith Avenue and War Memorial Drive) both still exist today.
[src:adelaide-footy-league/adelaide-footy-league-p01] The Jubilee Oval however was built upon by University of Adelaide in 1946.
[src:adelaide-footy-league/adelaide-footy-league-p01] In 1915, the season prior to WW1, there were 8 clubs - St Francis Xavier (Captain T.
[src:adelaide-footy-league/adelaide-footy-league-p01] Channon), Prince Alfred College (Captain A.H.
[src:adelaide-footy-league/adelaide-footy-league-p01] Pellew), St Peter's College (Captain R.D.
[src:adelaide-footy-league/adelaide-footy-league-p01] Throughout the history of the league there have been many clubs join and leave the league.
[src:adelaide-footy-league/adelaide-footy-league-p01] Affiliation peaked in 2001 with 72 clubs.
[src:adelaide-footy-league/adelaide-footy-league-p01] Of the founding clubs, only Adelaide University remains.
[src:adelaide-footy-league/adelaide-footy-league-p01] The 2010 season marked the 100th year of the league, with the last day in September won by Henley, who won their first Division 1 premiership in history.
[src:adelaide-footy-league/adelaide-footy-league-p01] In 2017 the league decided to change its name from the *South Australian Amateur Football League* to the *Adelaide Footy League*.
[src:adelaide-footy-league/adelaide-footy-league-p01] This table summarises the total Division 1 premierships and grand finals from 1911 to 2025.
[src:adelaide-footy-league/adelaide-footy-league-p01] Semaphore Central and Exeter merged to form "Port District FC" in 1979.
[src:adelaide-footy-league/adelaide-footy-league-p01] Nevertheless, PDFC set its date of establishment in 1873, as a continuity of Semaphore Central.
[src:adelaide-footy-league/adelaide-footy-league-p01] Previously known as Adelaide Teachers College from 1972 to 1979, Teachers College from 1935 to 1972, Teachers Training College from 1923 to 1934.
[src:adelaide-footy-league/adelaide-footy-league-p01] Merged with Alberton United and Ethelton to form Portland in 1997.
[src:adelaide-footy-league/adelaide-footy-league-p01] Moved to Southern Football League in 2009.
[src:adelaide-footy-league/adelaide-footy-league-p01] The current "Henley Sharks Football Club" was formed in 1994 as a merger of the Henley Districts, Old Scholars and Greek FC.
[src:adelaide-footy-league/adelaide-footy-league-p01] The following list summarises the Division 1 Grand Finals from 1911 to 2024.
[src:adelaide-footy-league/adelaide-footy-league-p02] The league has received media publicity over a number of incidents occurring at matches in recent years.
[src:adelaide-footy-league/adelaide-footy-league-p02] The league received media coverage in 2014 due to extreme scores in a number of games.
[src:adelaide-footy-league/adelaide-footy-league-p02] An attempt to oust then President Gino Capogreco in October 2013 failed when the vote was defeated at an extraordinary meeting of the league.
[src:adelaide-footy-league/adelaide-footy-league-p02] Capogreco was accused of altering a document and physically threatening a board member.
[src:adelaide-footy-league/adelaide-footy-league-p02] Capogreco was later defeated at the following AGM.
